40. 
Danilenko N, Lercher L, Kirkpatrick J, Gabel F, Codutti L,
Carlomagno T: Histone chaperone exploits intrinsic disorder to switch acetylation specificity. Nat Commun 2019, 10:3435
Through a combination of experiments and simulations, this work shows how polyelectrolyte interactions without structure formation between the charged disordered tails of the core histone H3 and the chaperone Vps75 play an important role in aiding the acetylation of specific lysine residues of H3 by the acetyltransferase Rtt109.
41. 
Turner AL, Watson M, Wilkins OG, Cato L, Travers A, Thomas JO, Stott K: Highly disordered histone H1-DNA model complexes and their condensates. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A 2018, 115:11964-11969 This study uses a range of biophysical methods to show that the intrinsically disordered C-terminal tail of linker histone H1 forms a high-affinity polyelectrolyte complex with double-stranded DNA without gain of structure. The authors further establish a link between the phosphorylation state of H1 and its coacervation with DNA, implying a potential mechanism of regulating chromatin compaction.
42. Gibbs EB, Kriwacki RW: Linker histones as liquid-like glue for chromatin. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A 2018, 115:11868-11870.
43. McGinty RK, Tan S: Nucleosome structure and function. Chem Rev 2015, 115:2255-2273.
44. Cristofari G, Ivanyi-Nagy R, Gabus C, Boulant S, Lavergne JP, Penin F, Darlix JL: The hepatitis C virus Core protein is a potent nucleic acid chaperone that directs dimerization of the viral(+) strand RNA in vitro. Nucleic Acids Res 2004, 32:2623-2631.
45. 
Holmstrom ED, Nettels D, Schuler B: Conformational plasticity of hepatitis C virus core protein enables RNA-induced formation of nucleocapsid-like particles. J Mol Biol 2018, 430:2453-2467 Using single-molecule spectroscopy, the authors show that the intrinsically disordered nucleocapsid domain of the hepatitis C virus core protein compacts but remains disordered and retains its 50 ns chain dynamics upon binding viral RNA.
